[1] Case update
- Thu 4 Oct 2018. Epidemiological situation report, DRC Ministry of Health
[in French, machine trans., edited]
https://us13.campaign-archive.com/?u=89e5755d2cca4840b1af93176&id=9363c70c25

The epidemiological situation of the Ebola virus disease in the provinces of North Kivu and Ituri dated 3 Oct 2018:
- a total of 165 cases of haemorrhagic fever have been reported in the region, of which 133 confirmed and 32 probable;
- Of the 133 confirmed, 74 died and 47 have recovered;
- 24 suspected cases are under investigation;
- 3 new confirmed cases, including 2 in Beni and 1 in Mabalako;
- 1 new person healed in Beni;
- no new deaths.

News of the response
Minister of health travels to Tchomia [Ituri]
---------------------------------------------
- On 4 Oct 2018, Dr Oly Ilunga Kalenga, minister of health, traveled to Tchomia in Ituri province with vice provincial governor Pacifique Keta and Congolese and international experts. The purpose of the trip was to assess the status of the Ebola response in the health zone and strengthen community engagement. The delegation visited the mobile laboratory of the National Institute for Biomedical Research (INRB), the new Ebola Treatment Center (ETC) under construction, and the port of Tchomia, where the minister talked with the young fishermen and travelers to encourage them to get involved and respect the preventive measures.
- In an interview with the local press, the minister regretted that despite the fact that more than 100 people have already died and more than 150 children have been orphaned or separated from their parents because of the epidemic, some people continue to doubt the existence of the disease. He added that whole families have disappeared because of this skepticism and resistance to rumors and misinformation. He reminded the journalists that their role was precisely to do this work of raising awareness and spreading the correct information.

Vaccination
-----------
- Since the start of vaccination on 8 Aug 2018, 14 017 people have been vaccinated, including 4557 in Beni [North Kivu], 4254 in Mabalako [North Kivu], 1632 in Mandima [Ituri], 1283 in Katwa [North Kivu], 1014 in Butembo [North Kivu], 307 in Bunia [Ituri], 355 in Tchomia [Ituri], 270 in Masereka [North Kivu], 224 in Komanda [Ituri], and 121 in Oicha [North Kivu].

--
communicated by:
ProMED-mail rapporteur Mary Marshall

[Direct interaction of the minister of health with the community should definitely be helpful. He encouraged the journalists to raise awareness of the disease, which also would be helpful, but possibly risky for them if there is resistance to their writing. - Mod.LK]

